[36;1mDESCRIPTION[0m
       [36;1mmmap[22;0m()  creates a new mapping in the virtual address space of the call‐
       ing process.  The starting address for the new mapping is specified  in
       [31;3;1maddr[24;0m.   The  [31;3;1mlength[24;0m argument specifies the length of the mapping (which
       must be greater than 0).

       If [31;3;1maddr[24;0m is NULL, then the kernel chooses the (page‐aligned) address  at
       which to create the mapping; this is the most portable method of creat‐
       ing  a new mapping.  If [31;3;1maddr[24;0m is not NULL, then the kernel takes it as a
       hint about where to place the mapping; on Linux, the kernel will pick a
       nearby page boundary (but always above or equal to the value  specified
       by [31;3;1m/proc/sys/vm/mmap_min_addr[24;0m) and attempt to create the mapping there.
       If another mapping already exists there, the kernel picks a new address
       that may or may not depend on the hint.  The address of the new mapping
       is returned as the result of the call.

       The contents of a file mapping (as opposed to an anonymous mapping; see
       [36;1mMAP_ANONYMOUS  [22;0mbelow),  are  initialized using [31;3;1mlength[24;0m bytes starting at
       offset [31;3;1moffset[24;0m in the file (or other object) referred to by the file de‐
       scriptor [31;3;1mfd[24;0m.  [31;3;1moffset[24;0m must be a multiple of the page size as returned by
       [31;3;1msysconf(_SC_PAGE_SIZE)[24;0m.

       After the [36;1mmmap[22;0m() call has returned, the file  descriptor,  [31;3;1mfd[24;0m,  can  be
       closed immediately without invalidating the mapping.

